<h1 class="hero-h">When Should I Hire a Fractional CMO? <em style="color:#00C853;font-style:italic;">Between $3M and $30M ARR, with a team to lead.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">The right window for a fractional CMO is narrower than most CEOs realize. Too early, and you do not yet have anything to manage; too late, and you need a full-time leader. Here's the timing framework.</p>
<div class="tldr"><div class="tldr-l">Short answer</div><p class="tldr-p">Hire a fractional CMO when you are between \$3M and \$30M in ARR, you already have at least 1-2 marketing executors, you can name a 12-month outcome, and the CEO will commit 2-3 hours/week to marketing decisions. Below \$3M, founder-led marketing usually wins. Above \$30M, full-time CMO is usually the right next step.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
<div style="max-width:880px;margin:0 auto;display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;gap:1rem;flex-wrap:wrap;font-size:0.78rem;color:#8FAF8F;">
<div>By <a href="/about" style="color:#F0FFF0;text-decoration:none;font-weight:500;">Bill Colbert</a> · <span style="color:#4A6A4A;">Founder, Treetop Growth Strategy</span></div>
<div style="color:#4A6A4A;">Published May 2026 · <a href="/content-library" style="color:#8FAF8F;text-decoration:none;">More from the library</a></div>
</div>
</div>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">The five timing signals</h2><ol class="ol"><li><strong>Revenue is between \$3M and \$30M ARR</strong> in a B2B model.</li><li><strong>You already have 1-2 marketing executors</strong> (or one strong marketing manager). A fractional CMO needs people to work through; absent that, hire the executor first.</li><li><strong>Founder-led marketing has hit its limit.</strong> The CEO can no longer carry it without losing focus on product, sales, or hiring.</li><li><strong>You can articulate a 12-month outcome</strong> (pipeline growth, brand recognition, conversion improvement).</li><li><strong>You can commit \$8K-\$20K/month for 12-18 months</strong> — and the CEO has 2-3 hours/week for marketing decisions.</li></ol></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Common premature signals</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Pre-PMF.</strong> If you are still searching for product-market fit, do not scale marketing yet. Fix the product.</li><li><strong>Below \$3M ARR.</strong> Founder voice usually outperforms a fractional CMO at this scale. Use the budget for a strong content marketer or paid media operator instead.</li><li><strong>Hiring to fix sales.</strong> A fractional CMO won't fix a sales problem. Consider a fractional CRO or sales coaching instead.</li><li><strong>No marketing team yet.</strong> Hire the executor first; the strategist later.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">Common late signals</h2><ul class="ul"><li><strong>Above \$30M ARR.</strong> You need a full-time CMO at this scale. A fractional can bridge during search, but is not the long-term answer.</li><li><strong>Five+ marketing people already.</strong> A fractional cannot lead a team that big well. Hire full-time.</li><li><strong>Marketing is the largest line item in your operating budget.</strong> Anything that big needs a full-time leader.</li></ul></div></section>
<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">The 30-second test</h2><p class="body">Answer yes or no to all five:</p><ol class="ol"><li>Are you between \$3M and \$30M ARR? (Y/N)</li><li>Do you have 1-2 marketing executors already? (Y/N)</li><li>Can you describe what "success in 12 months" looks like? (Y/N)</li><li>Will the CEO commit 2-3 hours/week to marketing decisions? (Y/N)</li><li>Can you commit \$8K-\$20K/month for 12-18 months? (Y/N)</li></ol><p class="body">Five yeses = now is the right time. Four yeses = address the gap first. Three or fewer = different solution.</p></div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner"><h2 class="h2">FAQ</h2>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How long should a fractional CMO engagement last?</h3><p class="faq-qa">12-18 months is the typical sweet spot. Shorter rarely compounds; longer often means the engagement needed to become a full-time hire.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Should I hire fractional or full-time?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Below \$15M ARR, fractional is usually right. \$15M-\$30M, either works depending on hiring market. Above \$30M, full-time is usually right.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">How much does a fractional CMO cost?</h3><p class="faq-qa">\$8K-\$25K/month for a B2B mid-market engagement, depending on time commitment and seniority.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">Can a fractional CMO build my team?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Yes. Many great engagements include hiring 1-2 marketers during the engagement. A good fractional knows the talent market.</p></div>
<div class="faq-q"><h3 class="faq-qh">What if I outgrow the fractional?</h3><p class="faq-qa">Plan for it. A good fractional helps you spec and recruit your full-time CMO when you outgrow the model.</p></div>
</div></section>

